      <p><bold>Theorem 3 </bold>Given a bifurcating supertree <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="1471-2148-11-205-i5.gif"/></inline-formula> and a bifurcating input tree <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="1471-2148-11-205-i1.gif"/></inline-formula>. Then <italic>d</italic><sup>+ </sup>= 2<italic>B</italic>, where <italic>B </italic>is the number of splits in <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="1471-2148-11-205-i5.gif"/></inline-formula> that are incompatible to at least one split in <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="1471-2148-11-205-i1.gif"/></inline-formula>.</p>
      <p><bold>Proof </bold>The proof is a modification of the proof for Theorem 2. The "good" taxa are placed in the same way and the bad taxa are placed <italic>onto </italic>any split corresponding to a conflicting split in <inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="1471-2148-11-205-i1.gif"/></inline-formula>. The resulting distance is then 2<italic>C </italic>+ 2(<italic>B - C</italic>) = 2<italic>B</italic>.    ■</p>
